The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 MusicWorld hums growth tunes 

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Rock roll

 Calcutta, Sept. 20: MusicWorld is expecting a turnover of Rs 90 crore in the current financial year against Rs 73 crore in 2004-05.

 The music and entertainment business of RPG Retail is on an expansion spree and will open a store in Mumbais Fort area tomorrow. This store, which will be open seven days a week, will be the 262nd outlet of MusicWorld.

 MusicWorld chief executive Subrata Chowdhury said the Mumbai market is as big as Rs 150-180 crore. MusicWorld plans to open three more shops in quick succession.

 The new store will have up to 20,000 albums covering different genres.

 The USP of the new store is its well-stocked home video section. There will also be MusicWorlds latest private label Footprints, a collection of 15 playback legends of old Hindi film songs, Chowdhury said.

 MusicWorld has a consumer request log (CRL) system, which enables music lovers to place requests for products not available off the shelf. MusicWorld intends to leverage its pan-India infrastructure to procure the titles registered by a consumer.

 MusicWorld general manager (operations and marketing) Sanjay Gupta said, The music industrys annual sale in India is around Rs 700 crore, while the home video market is around Rs 150-175 crore. Wherever MusicWorld is present, its market share is not less than 20 per cent. Mumbai is a large market for us.

 Regarding the surging demand for home videos, Gupta said VCD sales at MusicWorld outlets grew by 50 per cent last year, while DVD sales doubled.

 The first MusicWorld store was opened in 1997 in Chennai. Currently, the highest selling MusicWorld store is located at Park Street, Calcutta. Sales at this store is expected to reach Rs 12 crore this year against Rs 9 crore achieved last year.

 At present, there are four MusicWorld formats ? destination stores, express stores, franchisee stores and unplugged stores. There are 14 destination stores, 60 express stores, eight franchisee stores and 180 unplugged stores.




